	<div class="commentBody">
		<div id="comment_body_64694912"><p>Well, let's first address your question in the context of efficacy only, and then expand the scope to efficacy and safety (i.e., consider the risk/benefit profile).</p><p>The phrase "demonstrating an unequivocal effect" needs further clarification as it applies to the statistical interpretation of a study's outcome.  For instance, you could design a massive randomized and well-controlled study, collect data, and compute a highly significant $p$-value, but the effect size is tiny.  The treatment effect unequivocall<span class="substr"> </span></p></div>
	</div>

